    <item>
      <title>Re: Everquest's fundamental growth problem</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=SOE&amp;message.id=4697#M4697</link>
      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Interesting read.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I have a few suggestions:&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;1: Revamp all old world zones and starting cities. Introduce a new quest/dialog system to the game that is a bit more current. Introduce new quests for 1-50, and go back and adjust the old quest and rewards. Make the tutorial just that...a tutorial. Put a quest requirement or level restriction on the PoK books. Move the PoK newbie quests out and place the questing back in the starting cities. Revamp the water zones and get a new and improved immersive boat system going again...and have plenty of low end questing out there to inspire low level travel. Place in "Mages Guild Teleport Systems" in each mages guild in each of the 'starting' cities. Have it usable for a fee. Actually show the player 'levitating' over the land with neat sparklies...going through zonelines...till them get to the city mages guild they are going to, then 'beam' them down into it. Just like a griffon ride, but without the griffon basically. =) Would be amazing. You could even make it to where the player has to have already visited the place before they can be 'sent'.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;2: Revamp all old world dungeons, restructure the loot and spawns. Make quests in ALL the starting cities for dungeons in different level ranges...and include instructions on how to get to them...for new players. The quests would bring people together. Look into instancing for dungeons. People like that....it 'feels' better and more immersive.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;3: Tweak the entire downtime system. From death to regeneration rates. Put in different ways players can be 'buffed'...instead of it being potions ( which are expensive for a new player ) and player buffs ( encourages two boxing and 'donation' buffing ) put in things like EQ2 food and water idea, campsites ( player puts up a camp that has a timer on it ...while in the camp sitting down mana and hp come back at a much higher rate ...say each camp lasts 30 minutes..regen turns off if in combat ).&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;4: Treasure chests. Have them spawn around the world in monster camps and so on. Have a 'chance' to drop something magical.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;5: Institute "Age". Characters have "Age". Once a player has reached the top level they start growing 'old'. Once they reach an elderly state they have to retire from adventuring. All stats are drastcally reduced. If a player decided to 'retire' they are allowed to turn their PC into an NPC. The PC/NPC is then placed in a "hold" and gets put into the game by&amp;nbsp;a GM or DEV. This is the 'reward' for reaching that...they become a part of the lore and world. The PC/NPC is now unplayable by the account, but now the player can choose to make a new character. This character can have special 'advantages' depending on what class the retiring character was, and the new character gets one item from the retiring character as an inheritance, which will have lore on it that the player labeled. In this way an item could conceivably be passed down many many generations. Perhaps an item like this could actually gain in power during each passing...perhaps even gaining a voice of it's own.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;6: Place durability on items. And institute the 'binding' thing. This would help ensure the market for new players was reasonable.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Things like this would really draw in people. You could call it "Everquest: A Dynasty Reborn" .&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Britehawk&lt;/P&gt;</description>
